    content: `
      <p>"Is it worth it?" is one of the most common questions we ask ourselves. Is that expensive course worth it? Is moving to a new city worth it? Is leaving my relationship worth it? Is buying that house worth it? The question comes up dozens of times in our lives, and it never gets easier to answer.</p>

      <p>The problem is "worth it" is subjective. What's worth it to one person isn't to another. A 500-dollar concert ticket might be a once-in-a-lifetime experience for a music fan and a complete waste of money for someone who doesn't care about live music. Here's a framework to figure it out for yourself, based on your own values and circumstances.</p>

      <h2>The Cost-Benefit Ratio</h2>
      <p>List the costs (money, time, energy, stress, opportunity cost) and the benefits (growth, happiness, money, experience, relationships) on each side. Be honest about both. Most people overestimate benefits and underestimate costs when they want something, and do the opposite when they're afraid. Write both lists down and be brutally honest.</p>

      <p>If the benefits clearly outweigh the costs, it's worth it. If they're close, use our <a href="/">decision maker tool</a> to break the tie. Sometimes seeing a clear answer from an objective source helps you recognize what you truly feel.</p>

      <h2>The 72-Hour Rule</h2>
      <p>If you can wait 72 hours before deciding, do it. Impulse decisions to buy or quit are often regretted. After 3 days, if you still want it, the answer is yes. This rule is particularly effective for purchases, but it works for many types of decisions. The waiting period lets the initial emotional rush fade and reveals your true, lasting preference.</p>

      <p>For big financial decisions, extend this to 30 days. If you still want that expensive item or service after a month of thinking about it, the desire is genuine and not impulsive.</p>

      <h2>Ask Someone Who's Done It</h2>
      <p>The fastest way to know if something is worth it: find someone who's already done it and ask them. Their honest answer will save you months of deliberation. Most people love sharing their experiences, and their insights can reveal pros and cons you hadn't considered. Ask specific questions: "What was the hardest part?" "Would you do it again?" "What do you wish you'd known beforehand?"</p>

      <h2>The Regret Test</h2>
      <p>Imagine yourself in 5 years. Will you regret not doing this more than you'll regret doing it? Most people regret the things they didn't do far more than the things they did. Use this as a tiebreaker when the cost-benefit analysis is inconclusive.</p>

      <p>Still not sure? Try our <a href="/">free decision tool</a> and see how you feel about the answer. Sometimes the clarity you need comes from an outside perspective.</p>
    `
